Anwser: The size of compressed gz file size is 1.8G and the uncompressed is 13G. The run times of compressed gz file size is 18.761s and the uncompressed is 5.893s. Obviously, the compressed has smaller size but needs more time to run, while the uncompressed has larger size but save more time.Thus, when we consider about which type to choose, we need to choose based on the specific use case and requirements.

The wget command is a utility for downloading files from the web using the command line. The -nc option in the context of wget stands for âno-clobber,â and its primary purpose is to prevent overwriting existing files. In this question, wget -nc download the Price and Prejudice from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt if it does not exist locally or if it differs in size from the remote version.

  1. Whatâs the difference between the following two commands?
echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt
echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt

Answer: The difference between the two commands is that the first command will overwrite the file with the new text if it already exists, while the second command will add the new text to the end of the file without overwriting existing contentif it already exists.

  1. Using your favorite text editor (e.g., vi), type the following and save the file as middle.sh:
#!/bin/sh
# Select lines from the middle of a file.
# Usage: bash middle.sh filename end_line num_lines
head -n "$2" "$1" | tail -n "$3"

Using chmod to make the file executable by the owner, and run

./middle.sh pg42671.txt 20 5

Explain the output. Explain the meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in this shell script. Why do we need the first line of the shell script?

vi middle.sh
chmod +x middle.sh
./middle.sh pg42671.txt 20 5
Editor: R. W. Chapman

Release date: May 9, 2013 [eBook #42671]

Language: English

Answer: The output is 16-20 lines of the file pg42671.txt. "$1" is the pg42671.txt, which is the filename. "$2" is 20, which is the end_line. "$3" is 5, which is the num_lines. The first line is the shebang and specifies the interpreter to use. Without it, the script might be interpreted by a different shell, and the behavior could be different.

rm ./pg42671.txt

Answer: cal: Displays the current monthâs calendar.

cal 2024: Displays the calendar for the year 2024.

cal 9 1752: Displays a calendar for the month of September in the year 1752. There was a transition from September 2, 1752, to September 14, 1752. 11 days were skipped.

date: Displays the current date and time.

hostname: displays the name of the current host arch.

arch: Displays the computer architecture.

uname -a: Provides detailed information about the system, including the kernel version, machine type, and more.

uptime: Shows how long the system has been running and the current system load.

who am i: Displays the current userâs login name .

who: Lists the users who are currently logged in.

w: Displays information about the system and logged-in users.

id: Shows the user and group information for the current user.

last | head: Shows a list of last logged-in users.

echo {con,pre}{sent,fer}{s,ed}: Uses brace expansion to generate combinations and echoes them. For example, it prints âconsciences conscience conscious consciences presents presenter presented presentersâ.

time sleep 5: Measures the time it takes to execute the sleep 5 command.

history | tail: Displays the command history with the most recent commands.

Q6. Book

  1. Git clone the repository https://github.com/christophergandrud/Rep-Res-Book for the book Reproducible Research with R and RStudio to your local machine.

  2. Open the project by clicking rep-res-3rd-edition.Rproj and compile the book by clicking Build Book in the Build panel of RStudio. (Hint: I was able to build git_book and epub_book but not pdf_book.)

The point of this exercise is (1) to get the book for free and (2) to see an example how a complicated project such as a book can be organized in a reproducible way.
